<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900511-0035</DOCNO><DOCID>900511-0035.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Washington Post Co.:   Board Clears the Buy-Back   Of Up to 1 Million Shares</HL><DATE>05/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   WPO</CO><IN>BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)</IN><LP>   Washington Post Co.'s board cleared the company to buy onthe open market as many as one million shares of its Class Bcommon stock, currently trading at $241.50 each.   The board didn't set a price ceiling or a time limit forthe purchases. In New York Stock Exchange Composite tradingyesterday, the stock closed up $8.50 a share. At currentlevels the transaction would cost the company as much as$241.5 million.</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman said that since 1987 the company has purchasedabout 700,000 of its shares on the open market.   Peter Keefe, an analyst with Johnston, Lemon andamp; Co., notedthe buy-back strategy is common among companies in whichWarren E. Buffett is a major investor. Mr. Buffett, chairmanof Berkshire Hathaway Inc., controls 16.5% of WashingtonPost's Class B stock, which are nonvoting shares. Class Ashares are 100% controlled by the family of Katharine Graham,Washington Post chairman.   The media company publishes the Washington Post newspaperand Newsweek magazine.</TEXT></DOC>